 parapsychology is making the case, both theoretically and experimentally, that answers James's question in the affirmative. By separating what James passionately wanted to believe, based on common sense, from what his insights and researches led him to believe, Bricklin shows how James himself laid the groundwork for this more challenging view of existence. The non-reality of will, self, and time is consistent with James's psychology of volition, his epistemology of self, and his belief that Newtonian, objective, even-flowing time does not exist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPhilosophersxUnited States. 0aPhilosopherszUnited States. 0aPsychologistsxUnited States. 0aPsychologistszUnited States. 0aTranspersonal psychologyxUnited States. 0aTranspersonal psychology. 4aPsychology : Noetics/Consciousness Studies. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aPsychology : Transpersonal Psychology. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Mysticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Transpersonal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438456294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438456294/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles